properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds with severe and damaging gusts are expected or occurring. Strong west to northwest winds, with gusts of 110 km/h, this afternoon and tonight. Strong winds have moved into western Saskatchewan and will move eastward across the southern half of the province this evening. Gusts as high as 110 km/h will occur. The strong winds will weaken to below warning levels by Thursday morning, but it will remain blustery through the remainder of Thursday. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Drivers may lose control of their vehicles; tall vehicles are at risk of being overturned. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A very strong frontal system will track across Haida Gwaii Thursday evening and move onto the North Coast. Ahead of the front, winds will increase to southeast 80 to 100 km/h over Haida Gwaii Thursday morning then spread to North Vancouver Island in the afternoon and the North and Central Coast early in the evening. In its wake, the winds will ease to southerly 50 to 70 km/h. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain will fall this afternoon and this evening. Slippery conditions will occur. The freezing rain will move into western Manitoba later this afternoon and will end late this evening or overnight. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
